## Objective
- Build the complete `gridcalc-xl` Python library per SPEC.md: a pure-logic in-memory multi-sheet spreadsheet engine with one public class `Workbook`, formula parsing/evaluation, undo/redo, persistence, volatile recalculation, and incremental recomputation. Run `pytest -q` from repo root with all tests green.

## Important Details
- **Spec location**: `/Users/arden/code/ornith-loopspace-experiments/gridcalc-xl/runs/solo/SPEC.md`
- **Repo state at start**: only `.git/`, `.gitignore`, `opencode.json`, `SPEC.md` — no source code existed
- **Package structure created**: `gridcalc/` with `__init__.py`, `lexer.py`, `ast.py`, `parser.py`, `evaluator.py`, `sheet.py`, `workbook.py`
- **No tests file exists yet** — must be created
- **No `pytest` run has been executed yet** — unknown if code is correct
- **Key spec constraints**: 256-cell chain, 512-char source, 32-paren depth, 4096-char string limit, 2^63 magnitude limit, no floats, no file I/O, no deletion APIs, undo-only state reversal, string persistence round-trip equivalence, per-sheet eval_count observable across all operations
- **R12 iterative preference**: spec prefers iterative engine but allows raised recursion limit if set once at import with R12 comment; current implementation uses recursion
- **R17 copy rewriting**: character-level REF token rewriting preserving all non-REF characters exactly; out-of-grid refs become `#REF!`
- **R19 undo/redo**: LIFO journal, add_sheet undo removes sheet, redo re-applies; eval_count lifecycle preserved per sheet name
- **R24 persistence**: journal empty after loading, clock/sheets/cells/names round-trip, no bool in stored cells
- **R26 volatile**: clock-driven NOW(), eval_count increments on every volatile cell evaluation
- **R28 bounds**: 256 formula cells, 512 char source, 4096 char string, 2^63 magnitude

## Work State
### Completed
- Created `gridcalc/__init__.py` exporting `Workbook`
- Created `gridcalc/lexer.py` — tokenizer producing Token objects for all formula grammar tokens (INT, STRING, IDENT, $, !, :, (, ), ,, +, -, *, /, =, <>, <, <=, >, >=, #REF!, EOF)
- Created `gridcalc/ast.py` — AST node classes (IntLit, StringLit, Ref, Name, HashRef, Range, UnaryMinus, BinOp, FuncCall)
- Created `gridcalc/parser.py` — recursive-descent parser handling full grammar with $ marks, sheet qualifiers, ranges, all 8 functions (SUM/MIN/MAX/COUNT/CONCAT/LEN/IF/NOW)
- Created `gridcalc/evaluator.py` — formula evaluator with cycle detection, error ordering (R5 left-to-right short-circuit), string typing (R13), range visit order (row-major), named range resolution, sheet qualifiers, caching, eval_count tracking, magnitude/length bounds checking
- Created `gridcalc/sheet.py` — Sheet class with set/get/copy/define_name, copy-rewrite via character-level REF token scanning, name validation (R18), qualified target support (R23)
- Created `gridcalc/workbook.py` — Workbook class with add_sheet/sheet/sheet_names, clock/advance_clock, undo/redo with full journal entry types, to_json/from_json persistence, reference closure computation, touch set computation, eval_count lifecycle preservation

### Active
- Code is written but **never tested** — no pytest run has been executed
- Need to verify parser handles all edge cases (e.g., `$` before column letter in `_primary`, single-letter IDENTs, function names not followed by `(`)
- Need to verify evaluator handles all R5 error ordering cases correctly
- Need to verify copy rewriting handles all R17 cases (qualified refs, ranges, out-of-grid, leading-zero refs kept verbatim)
- Need to verify undo/redo handles add_sheet lifecycle correctly
- Need to verify persistence round-trip preserves eval semantics

### Blocked
- **No tests exist yet** — must create test file(s) covering all 10 acceptance groups (R1-R12, R13-R15, R16-R17, R18, R19-R20, R21-R23, R24-R25, R26-R27, R28)
- **No pytest run executed** — unknown if implementation is correct
- Parser may have issues with `$` token handling in `_primary` when `$` appears before a REF-matching IDENT (the `$` token is separate and needs to be consumed before the IDENT)
- The `_primary` method's IDENT branch for REF shape doesn't check for a leading `$` token that may precede the IDENT — this is a bug since `$A1` tokenizes as `[$, IDENT(A), INT(1)]` and the `$` is not consumed before entering the IDENT branch

## Next Move
1. Fix the parser bug: in `_primary`, when an IDENT matches REF shape, check if the previous token (or current position) has an unconsumed `$` — restructure so `$` is consumed before IDENT in the REF path. The current code has `_T_DOLLAR` check before IDENT, but the IDENT branch for REF shape doesn't handle the case where `$` was already consumed by the `_T_DOLLAR` branch — need to verify the flow is correct.
2. Run `pytest -q` from repo root to identify failures, then fix them iteratively until green.
